Fixed #33003 - Avoided updating the clone's __dict__ if no kwargs are given.

For a small performance benefit, it's cheaper to check for an empty dictionary than it is to always try and apply one.
Keyword arguments are only used by Prefetch.__getstate__, where it is acceptable to be a few nanoseconds slower to do the right thing and is comparatively rare.

Fixed #32983 -- Added system check for redundant related_name on symmetrical M2M fields.

Since ManyToManyFields defined with `symmetrical=True` do not add a
related field to the target model, including a `related_name` argument
will never do what the coder likely expects. This makes including
a related_name with a symmetrical model raise a system check warning.

python slicing-notation. Added a new class SliceableF that handles
identification of sliceable fields. Step-argument is not supported.

Fixed #32983 -- Made related_name on symmetric field an error.

Since ManyToManyFields defined with `symmetrical=True` do not add a
related field to the target model, including a `related_name` argument
will never do what the coder likely expects. Thus, this makes including
a related_name with symmetrical an error.

This error may show up on existing projects, but in all cases the
developers should be able to simply remove the related_name from the
field definition and behavior should stay unchanged. In other worse, the
extra argument is very likely not serving a purpose.

Fixed #32919 -- Optimized lexing & parsing of templates.

This optimizes:
- Lexer.create_token() by avoiding startswith() calls,
- Parser.parse() by re-using the token type enum's value,
- Parser.extend_nodelist() by removing unnecessary isinstance() check,
- some Node subclasses by removing the implicit "nodelist" from
  "child_nodelists",
- Variable.__init__() by avoiding startswith() calls.

Refs #28455 - Replace contextmanager decorator with a custom class which toggles the states on enter/exit.

This is substantially faster than using the decorator method
- decorator takes 1.1µs to execute, or 2µs if used correctly in a `with ...:` statement;
- custom class takes 300ns to execute, or 900ns if used correctly in a `with ...:` statement.

Refs #28455 - Implemented clone avoidance for simple prefetch_related usages.

Given a QuerySet like `get_user_model().objects.prefetch_related('groups')` this will cause fewer clones to be run, because the underlying `manager.get_queryset()` call should return a freshly instantiated per-instance QuerySet which doesn't need subsequent cloning.

For the cases where a `Prefetch()` object is used and `_apply_rel_filters` is executed directly, it cannot be known whether the QuerySet is safe to mutate in place and we must assume it isn't, and clone/chain it appropriately, thus there is little benefit, unless the database alias differs in which case it would be -1 clone per call.

Based on work originally done by Anssi Kääriäinen and Tim Graham

Refs #32940 -- Removed unnecessary branch in Node.add().

The "data in self.children" branch was causing data.__eq__ to be
called for each entries in "self.children" which resulted in a huge
slowdown during queryset construction.

It's purpose was to prevent queries of the form
    Model.objects.filter(foo='bar').filter(foo='bar')
from resulting in
    WHERE foo='bar' AND foo='bar'
but it's not covered by the suite and has arguable performance benefits
since it's not very common and SQL engines are usually very good at
folding/optimizing these.

See also #32632 for prior discussion around comparing data to the
Node's children.

Co-authored-by: Nick Pope <nick@nickpope.me.uk>

Refs #10929 -- Deprecated forced empty result value for PostgreSQL aggregates.

This deprecates forcing a return value for ArrayAgg, JSONBAgg, and

`runserver` command does not use the `--verbosity` option because
it already writes out every request it accepts. This command also
does not use `--traceback` option because the server errors are
also already caught and the tracebacks are printed out. Refer to
the ticket #15132.

Removed raising RuntimeError from shuffle() method.

There’s no need to raise an error if two items have the same hash value. Instead, we can secondarily sort by the key values to get a consistent ordering. Since hashes are based upon the seed, two tests that collide with one seed are highly unlikely to collide with another seed, so they get shuffled rather than always run in alphabetical order.

``nonform`` when rendering the error list. This allows a custom
ErrorList class to make a distinction in field errors, non-field errors
of forms and non-form errors of FormSets when rendering error messages.

Fixed #32840 - Avoided calling Field.__eq__ in the common case.

Where no output_field was provided and it defaulted to self, comparing self to self
was unnecessarily performed.
Short circuiting obviates 1 isinstance test + 2 getattr calls per column.

If an output_field is given, it *may* still compare as equal to self,
intentionally or through coincidental attributes, so may not be ignored completely.

Co-authored-by: Chris Jerdonek <chris.jerdonek@gmail.com>

Used urlparse and urlsplit from urllib

The bespoke _urlparse and _urlsplit methods were included
in Django so that a patch awiating merge to Python could be applied.
This patch has now been merged into Python and backported to Python 3.8
and so special methods in Django are no longer required.

Allow the return value of model_to_dict method to contain non-writable fields

I like to use this method in my personal projects, It can
perfectly convert model object into dictionary. But the
exported dictionary does not contain fields whose editable
attribute is False, which caused me a lot of trouble.

model_to_dict method is only used in django/forms/models.py
in the entire Django project, so such changes are safe.

If an output_field is given, it *may* still compare as equal to self (intentionally or through coincidental attributes) so may not be ignored completely.

Refs #26430 -- Re-introduced empty aggregation optimization.

The introduction of the Expression.empty_aggregate_value interface
allows the compilation stage to enable the EmptyResultSet optimization
if all the aggregates expressions implement it.

This also removes unnecessary RegrCount/Count.convert_value() methods.
Disabling the empty result set aggregation optimization when it wasn't
appropriate prevented None returned for a Count aggregation value.

Thanks Nick Pope for the review.

Fixed #32889 -- Allowed per-request sync_to_async context in ASGIHandler .

By using a asgiref's ThreadSensitiveContext context manager, requests
will be able to execute independently of other requests when sync work
is involved.

Prior to this commit, a single global thread was used to execute any
sync work independent of the request from which that work was scheduled.
This could result in contention for the global sync thread in the case
of a slow sync function.

Requests are now isolated to their own sync thread.

Fixed #32889 -- Allowed per-request sync_to_async context in ASGIHandler.

By using a asgiref's ThreadSensitiveContext context manager, requests
will be able to execute independently of other requests when sync work
is involved.

Prior to this commit, a single global thread was used to execute any
sync work independent of the request from which that work was scheduled.
This could result in contention for the global sync thread in the case
of a slow sync function.

Requests are now isolated to their own sync thread.

Fixed #32807 -- Allowed JSONField.bound_data to handle None as data

This change prevents an exception from being raised during form
rendering when a JSONField is missing from form data, bringing the
behaviour of JSONField in line with other fields in this case.
Specifically, a blank field is rendered, accompanied by a validation
error if the field is required.

Thanks to @AlexHill for the initial patch.

Removed options parameter from djangoAdminSelect2.

It seems this parameter has never been used internally, so to avoid

ContentType.model_class() in .get_for_models()

model_class(), when get_for_models() is called on manager and some
content type is not in cache a query is made to load them from DB,
if at last one is found then ContentType.model_class() is called on
loaded objects which causes AttributeError to be raised.

Fixed #32824 -- Improved performance of NodeList.render().

This avoids the following:
 - checking that each item in the nodelist is a subclass of Node,
 - calling str() on the render_annotated() output, because it's
   documented that Node.render() must return a string,
 - calling mark_safe() on the output, when the value to be wrapped is
   definitively known to be a string because the result of ''.join()
   is always of that type,
 - using an intermediate list to store each individual string.

Fixed #32824 -- Improved performance of NodeList.render().

This avoids the following:
 - checking that each item in the nodelist is a subclass of Node,
 - calling str() on the render_annotated() output, because it's
   documented that Node.render() must return a string,
 - calling mark_safe() on the output, when the value to be wrapped is
   definitively known to be a string because the result of ''.join()
   is always of that type,
 - using an intermediate list to store each individual string.

Refs #27734 -- Prevented creation of more parallel workers than TestCases.

The parallel test runner uses multiple workers to distribute the
workload. These workers are assigned a worker ID using a globally
incremented variable, which determines what test database to connect
to. When the worker ID surpasses the test database IDs Django will
crash.

This reduce likelihood of crashing parallel tests because
ParallelTestSuite will no longer create more workers than TestCases.

It won't eliminate the problem completely though because there are
other circumstances in which new workers can be created which can then
be assigned an "illegal" worker ID.

Refs #27734 -- Reduced likelihood of crashing parallel tests

The parallel test runner uses multiple workers to distribute the
workload. These workers are assigned a worker ID using a globally
incremented variable, and this worker ID determines what test database
to connect to. When the worker ID surpasses the test database IDs Django
will crash.

Say, you wanted to run 2 testcases on a 4-core CPU in parallel. Before
this patch Django would start out by creating 2 test databases and 4
processes, leading to sporadic crashes.

With this changeset Django starts out with 4 test databases and 2
processes, greatly reducing the likelihood of it going awry.

It won't eliminate the problem completely though because there are other
circumstances in which new workers can be created which can then be
assigned an "illegal" worker ID.

- using an intermediate list to store each individual string.

Refs #32814 - Implemented a specialised version of render_annotated for TextNode instances.

Avoiding the call to render() nets a small performance gain; most Node subclasses do _something_ when the render method is called, which may require exception catching & the addition of debug information, but TextNode is special in that it just returns the underlying str and doesn't even attempt a cast on it, so the render_annotated method can do exactly the same and skip the intermediate steps.

Fixed #32640 -- Made ModelBase.add_to_class() more careful

ModelBase.add_to_class(), used for adding generated attributes to model classes,
used to add these attributes without checking if they already exist. In cases
where these attributes were defined on the same model, this could cause
unintended consequences.

Fixed #32640 -- Made ModelBase.add_to_class() more careful

ModelBase.add_to_class(), used for adding generated attributes to model classes,
used to add these attributes without checking if they already exist. In cases
where these attributes were defined on the same model, this could cause
unintended consequences.

Refs #32814 - Implemented a specialised version of render_annotated for TextNode instances.

Most Node subclasses do _something_ when the render method is called, which may require exception catching & the addition of debug information, but TextNode is special in that it just returns the underlying str and doesn't even attempt a cast on it, so the render_annotated method can do exactly the same and skip the intermediate steps.

Refs #32668 -- Simplified get_test_modules() in runtests.py.

This simplifies runtests.py's get_test_modules() in a few ways.  For
example, it changes the function to yield strings instead of returning
pairs of strings, which simplifies the calling code.

This commit also changes SUBDIRS_TO_SKIP from a list to a dict since
the directories to skip depend on the parent directory.

Fix incorrect generation fo gin index with OpClass

Currently this index definition:
            GinIndex(OpClass(Upper("first_name"), name="gin_trgm_ops"), name="policy_first_name_upper_gin"),
generates:
CREATE INDEX "policy_first_name_upper_gin" ON "main_policy" USING gin ((UPPER("first_name") gin_trgm_ops))

This doesn't work, due to the bonus set of ().

The change I'm proposing above results in the index def above to generate:

CREATE INDEX "policy_last_name_upper_gin" ON "main_policy" USING gin (UPPER("last_name") gin_trgm_ops)

which does the right thing.

I am not super familiar with the code base - so I'm not sure if this would have negative impact on other usecases.

Fixed #123 -- cache_page decorator doesn't work for cross-browser

https://code.djangoproject.com/ticket/32774

**The root cause:**
- First load using Postman:
  - default header: Accept: */*

- Second load using Firefox:
  - default header: Accept: 'text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,image/webp,*/*;q=0.8'

=> First load's **cache_key** != Second load's **cache_key**

Refs #27734 -- Reduced likelihood of crashing parallel tests

The parallel test runner uses multiple workers to distribute the
workload. These workers are assigned a worker ID using a globally
incremented variable, and this worker ID determines what test database
to connect to. When the worker ID surpasses the test database IDs Django
will crash.

Say, you wanted to run 2 testcases on a 4-core CPU in parallel. Before
this patch Django would start out by creating 2 test databases and 4
processes, leading to sporadic crashes.

With this changeset Django starts out with 4 test databases and 2
processes, greatly reducing the likelihood of it going awry.

It won't eliminate the problem completely though because there are other
circumstances in which new workers can be created which can then be
assigned an "illegal" worker ID.

Fixed #32503 -- Reverted "Fixed #30712 -- Allowed BLOB/TEXT defaults on MySQL 8.0.13+."

This reverts commit 6b16c91157512587017e9178d066ed1a683e7795.

MySQL 8.0.13+ supports defaults on BLOB/TEXT columns but only when
adding a new column. Django doesn't use database defaults so they are
only useful to set values for existing rows which is not the case here.

Thanks Matt Westcott for the report.

I was quite confused how the DB cache was able to cull expired cache entries, asked on IRC and received this response. I think it'd be good to include this because others like me might be concerned that the timeout totally doesn't work on some backends. It does, of course (django is wonderful), and the implementation is clever enough to note.

redirects adding a language code to a path can be inappropriate cached by
HTTP caches

determine where to redirect to, then it should add a Vary header to the
redirect so that caches know what to do when caching the redirect
itself.

Fixed #????? -- Avoided crash in `DateFormat` for subclasses of `datetime.date`.

As `datetime.datetime` is a subclass of `datetime.date`, if we only want
dates we need to check that an object is an instance of the latter but
not the former. Using `type(...) is ...` prevents this check from
working correctly for other custom subclasses of `datetime.date`.

As a result, using any time-related format specifiers with a custom
subclass of `datetime.date` will not raise the expected `TypeError`.

Fixed #????? -- Avoided crash in `DateFormat` for subclasses of `datetime.date`.

As `datetime.datetime` is a subclass of `datetime.date`, if we only want
dates we need to check that an object is an instance of the latter but
not the former. Using `type(...) is ...` prevents this check from
working correctly for other custom subclasses of `datetime.date`.

As a result, using any time-related format specifiers with a custom
subclass of `datetime.date` will not raise the expected `TypeError`.

which are dynamically generated and, otherwise, show up as broken links.

We also ignore links to resources that require authentication.

Refs #32317 -- Simplified find_fixtures() in loaddata command.

This always replaces 'fixture_name' with its base name, which preserves
the previous behavior, because os.path.basename() was not called only on
relative paths without os.path.sep i.e. when base name was equal to the
file name.

This also changes os.path.dirname() and os.path.basename() calls to the
equivalent os.path.split() call.

Update signals.txt

As per the additional note: signals running in a post_save() may notify remote systems too soon for them to read data.

This happened when using MQTT to notify a remote 'desktop' django app to reload an object due to db changes.

I solved this issue and then found that others had similar problems:
https://ken-dev.info/django-tricks/2019/10/04/django-signals-in-transaction.html

I hope I have the syntax correct as I have not done a local build.

Fixed #32718 -- Relaxed file name validation in FileField.

- Validate filename returned by FileField.upload_to() not a filename
  passed to the FileField.generate_filename() (upload_to() may
  completely ignored passed filename).
- Allow relative paths (without dot segments) in the generated filename.

Thanks to Jakub Kleň for the report and review.
Thanks to all folks for checking this patch on existing projects.
Thanks Florian Apolloner and Markus Holtermann for the discussion and
implementation idea.

Regression in 0b79eb36915d178aef5c6a7bbce71b1e76d376d3.

Allow squashed migrations to also be squashed

 In order to support multi-level squashing, we need to be a bit smarter
 about how we traverse replacements. The solution here introduces some
 extra checks on squashed migrations (mainly a lookup for whether its
 replacements need to be squashed first), but the performance hit
 shouldn't be very large.

Fixed #32713, Fixed CVE-2021-32052 -- Prevented newlines and tabs from being accepted in URLValidator on Python 3.9.5+.

In Python 3.9.5+ urllib.parse() automatically removes ASCII newlines
and tabs from URLs [1, 2]. Unfortunately it created an issue in
the URLValidator. URLValidator uses urllib.urlsplit() and
urllib.urlunsplit() for creating a URL variant with Punycode which no
longer contains newlines and tabs in Python 3.9.5+. As a consequence,
the regular expression matched the URL (without unsafe characters) and
the source value (with unsafe characters) was considered valid.

[1] https://bugs.python.org/issue43882 and
[2] https://github.com/python/cpython/commit/76cd81d60310d65d01f9d7b48a8985d8ab89c8b4

Fixed #32713, Fixed CVE-2021-32052 -- Prevented newlines and tabs from being accepted in URLValidator on Python 3.9.5+.

In Python 3.9.5+ urllib.parse() automatically removes ASCII newlines
and tabs from URLs [1, 2]. Unfortunately it created an issue in
the URLValidator. URLValidator uses urllib.urlsplit() and
urllib.urlunsplit() for creating a URL variant with Punycode which no
longer contains newlines and tabs in Python 3.9.5+. As a consequence,
the regular expression matched the URL (without unsafe characters) and
the source value (with unsafe characters) was considered valid.

[1] https://bugs.python.org/issue43882 and
[2] https://github.com/python/cpython/commit/76cd81d60310d65d01f9d7b48a8985d8ab89c8b4

the URLValidator. URLValidator uses urllib.urlsplit() and
urllib.urlunsplit() for creating a URL variant with Punycode which no
longer contains newlines and tabs in Python 3.9.5+. As a consequence,
the regular expression matched the URL (without unsafe characters) and
the source value (with unsafe characters) was considered valid.

[1] https://bugs.python.org/issue43882 and
[2] https://github.com/python/cpython/commit/76cd81d60310d65d01f9d7b48a8985d8ab89c8b4

Fixed #32479 -- Implemented automatic fallbacks for various Chinese languages.

Changed implementation of `get_supported_language_variant`, so the
function will check if a language is supported by looking at:
1. The language code passed to the function.
2. Fallbacks language code from the LANG_INFO, if any.
3. All the variations of the language code in decreasing order of
   specificity, by stripping away suffixes separated by hyphens ('-').

E.g. for the language code like 'zh-Hans-HK' it would check:
1. zh-Hans-HK
2. Fallback from LANG_INFO
3. zh-Hans
4. zh

Fixed #32479 -- Implemented automatic fallbacks for various Chinese languages.

Refs #32695 -- Changed method that creates Permissions

Django Permissions were created with bulk_create() method which
results in not triggering pre_save and post_save signal. By using
create() method, it will enable developers to act on Permission
creation.

Removed unnecessary reuse_with_filtered_relation argument from Query methods.

In Query.join() the argument reuse_with_filtered_relation was used to
determine whether to use == or .equals(). As this area of code is
related to aliases, we only expect an instance of Join or BaseTable to
be provided - the only two classes that provide .equals().

In both cases, the implementations of __eq__() and equals() are based
on use of the "identity" property. __eq__() performs an isinstance()
check first, returning NotImplemented if required. BaseTable.equals()
then does a straightforward equality check on "identity". Join.equals()
is a little bit different as it skips checking the last element of the
"identity" property: filtered_relation. This was only included
previously when the with_filtered_relation argument was True, impossible
since bbf141bcdc31f1324048af9233583a523ac54c94.

Fixed #32632, Fixed #32657 -- Removed flawed support for Subquery deconstruction.

Subquery deconstruction support required implementing complex and
expensive equality rules for sql.Query objects for little benefit as
the latter cannot themselves be made deconstructible to their reference
to model classes.

Making Expression @deconstructible and not BaseExpression allows
interested parties to conform to the "expression" API even if they are
not deconstructible as it's only a requirement for expressions allowed
in Model fields and meta options (e.g. constraints, indexes).

Thanks Phillip Cutter for the report.

This also fixes a performance regression in bbf141bcdc31f1324048af9233583a523ac54c94.

Removed unnecessary reuse_with_filtered_relation argument.

In ``Query.join()`` the argument ``reuse_with_filtered_relation`` was
used to determine whether to use ``==`` or ``.equals()``. As this area
of code is related to aliases, we only expect an instance of ``Join``
or ``BaseTable`` to be provided - the only two classes that provide
``.equals()``.

In both cases, the implementations of ``.__eq__()`` and ``.equals()``
are based on use of the ``.identity`` property. ``.__eq__()`` performs
an ``isinstance()`` check first, returning ``NotImplemented`` if
required. ``BaseTable.equals()`` then does a straightforward equality
check on ``.identity``. ``Join.equals()`` is a little bit different as
it skips checking the last element of the ``.identity`` property:
``.filtered_relation``. This was only included previously when the
``with_filtered_relation`` argument was ``True``, impossible since
bbf141bcdc31f1324048af9233583a523ac54c94.

In both cases, the implementations of ``.__eq__()`` and ``.equals()``
are based on use of the ``.identity`` property. ``.__eq__()`` performs
an ``isinstance()`` check first, returning ``NotImplemented`` if
required. ``BaseTable.equals()`` then does a straightforward equality
check on ``.identity``. ``Join.equals()`` is a little bit different as
it skips checking the last element of the ``.identity`` property:
``.filtered_relation``. This was only included previously when the
``with_filtered_relation`` argument was ``True``, impossible since
bbf141bcdc31f1324048af9233583a523ac54c94.

Fixed #32632, Fixed #32657 -- Removed flawed support for Subquery deconstruction.

Subquery deconstruction support required implementing complex and
expensive equality rules for sql.Query objects for little benefit as
the latter cannot themselves be made deconstructible to their reference
to model classes.

Making Expression @deconstructible and not BaseExpression allows
interested parties to conform to the "expression" API even if they are
not deconstructible as it's only a requirement for expressions allowed
in Model fields and meta options (e.g. constraints, indexes).

Thanks Phillip Cutter for the report.

This also fixes a performance regression in bbf141bcdc31f1324048af9233583a523ac54c94.

Fixed #32650 -- Fixed handling subquery aliasing on queryset combination.

This issue started manifesting itself when nesting a combined subquery
relying on exclude() since 8593e162c9cb63a6c0b06daf045bc1c21eb4d7c1 but
sql.Query.combine never properly handled subqueries outer refs in the
first place, see QuerySetBitwiseOperationTests.test_subquery_aliases()
(refs #27149).

Thanks Raffaele Salmaso for the report.

Fixed #32664 -- Made PasswordResetTokenGenerator.secret validation lazy.

Django apps initialization to run management command triggers the admin
autodiscovery. Importing django.contrib.auth.tokens creates an instance
of PasswordResetTokenGenerator which required a SECRET_KEY.

For several management commands, the token generator is unused. It
should only complain about a missing SECRET_KEY when it is used.

Dynamically calculate sidebar height based on headers

The current sticky nav bar on admin anchors past the page when you have
many different apps and model because it is configured to 100vh.

Calculating the height of the header not an option because the header
scrolls off the page when there is a large amount of content on the page.

This uses JavaScript to dynamically size the sidebar on scroll/resize
so that it always properly fits the view regardless of the header's size
or whether it is on, or off, the page.

Fixed #32664 -- Allowed running makemigrations without a SECRET_KEY.

Django apps initialization to run management command triggers the admin
autodiscovery. The auth admin imports from django.contrib.auth.forms,
which imports the django.contrib.auth.tokens, instantiating a
PasswordResetTokenGenerator that requires a SECRET_KEY.

For several management commands, the token generator is unused. It
should only complain about a missing SECRET_KEY when it is used.

Removed obsolete version check in setup.py.

This was originally added to ensure that Django 2.0+ could not be
installed on Python 2.7 or earlier, in particular where the version of
pip or setuptools being used did not support the python_requires
argument.

Unfortunately, as REQUIRED_PYTHON has been bumped, this check no longer
satisfies its original purpose and could be misleading, e.g. if
REQUIRED_PYTHON is 3.8 and CURRENT_PYTHON is 3.7 it would request that
Django < 2 is installed, but there are later versions of Django that
support Python 3.7.

By the time Django 4 is released in December 2021, the python_requires
argument will have been supported for over five years, and Python 2 will
have been EOL for nearly two years, so we can remove this check.

See https://packaging.python.org/guides/distributing-packages-using-setuptools/#python-requires

Removed obsolete version check in setup.py.

This was originally added to ensure that Django 2.0+ could not be
installed on Python 2.7 or earlier, in particular where the version of
pip or setuptools being used did not support the python_requires
argument.

Unfortunately, as REQUIRED_PYTHON has been bumped, this check no longer
satisfies its original purpose and could be misleading, e.g. if
REQUIRED_PYTHON is 3.8 and CURRENT_PYTHON is 3.7 it would request that
Django < 2 is installed, but there are later versions of Django that
support Python 3.7.

By the time Django 4 is released in December 2021, the python_requires
argument will have been supported for over five years, and Python 2 will
have been EOL for nearly two years, so we can remove this check.

See https://packaging.python.org/guides/distributing-packages-using-setuptools/#python-requires

make from_email argument optional in send_mail

the django docs state that, while sending mail, if no from_email is passed, it will use the `DEFAULT_FROM_EMAIL`.
source: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/3.1/topics/email/

However, when using the send_mail function, the `from_email` argument is not optional.
resolves https://code.djangoproject.com/ticket/32633#ticket
giving a default value of `None` to it will resolve this issue.

Fixed #32316 -- Deferred accessing __file__.

Deferred accessing the module-global variable __file__ because the
Python import API does not guarantee it always exists—in particular, it
does not exist in certain "frozen" environments. The following changes
advanced this goal.

Thanks to Carlton Gibson, Tom Forbes, Mariusz Felisiak, and Shreyas
Ravi for review and feedback.

Fixed #32610 -- Fixed get_git_changeset() on Linux.

shell=True is required on Windows. Unfortunately passing a sequence to
subprocess.run() behaves differently on Linux, i.e. the first item
specifies the command string, and any additional items are treated as
additional arguments to the shell itself.

https://docs.python.org/3.9/library/subprocess.html#subprocess.Popen
https://docs.python.org/3.9/library/subprocess.html#converting-an-argument-sequence-to-a-string-on-windows

Regression in a44d80f88e22eda24dacef48e368895ebea96635.

Fixed #32316 -- Deferred accessing __file__.

Deferred accessing the module-global variable __file__ because the
Python import API does not guarantee it always exists—in particular, it
does not exist in certain "frozen" environments. The following changes
advanced this goal.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in django.forms.renderers by
  removing the undocumented, module-level constant ROOT, which had been
  used in only one cached property.

* Prevented a crash during Django pre-alpha development if __file__ is
  missing by teaching django.utils.version.get_git_changeset to return
  None instead of raising NameError.

  django.__version__ is computed when django is first imported. If
  django.VERSION is pre-alpha, django.utils.version.get_version
  calls django.utils.version.get_git_changeset.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in django.views.debug by
  by removing the the undocumented, module-level constant CURRENT_DIR,
  which had been used only in the module itself. Replaced it with a
  module-level private function `builtin_template_path` that refactors
  and centralizes finding built-in templates for the entire module.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in
  django.contrib.auth.password_validation by converting
  CommonPasswordValidator's class constant DEFAULT_PASSWORD_LIST_PATH
  into a cached property. It is used only in one place, the class's
  instance constructor. While the nature of DEFAULT_PASSWORD_LIST_PATH
  is not documented, its existence can be inferred from the docs for the
  [constructor's signature].

  During review there was some [back]-[and]-[forth] about whether to use Python
  3.8's functools.cached_property (GH-13915 raised the minimum supported
  version to 3.8) or django.utils.functional.cached_property (#30949 is not yet
  accepted), but [settled] on the latter.

Thanks to @carltongibson, @orf, @shreyasravi, and @felixxm for review and
feedback.

[constructor's signature]: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/3.1/topics/auth/passwords/#django.contrib.auth.password_validation.CommonPasswordValidator
[back]: https://github.com/django/django/pull/13841#discussion_r551560566
[and]: https://github.com/django/django/pull/13841#discussion_r570091753
[forth]: https://github.com/django/django/pull/13841#discussion_r601156906
[settled]: https://github.com/django/django/pull/13841#discussion_r602107536

it's unintended and have side-effects such as adding `self` to the
signature.

views with class-based views.

Fixed #32316 -- Deferred accessing __file__.

Deferred accessing the module-global variable __file__ because the
Python import API does not guarantee it always exists—in particular, it
does not exist in certain "frozen" environments. The following changes
advanced this goal.

* Corrected or removed misleading code comments.

  The comment in questioner.py about needing getattr() for __file__ only
  in PY36 and older is true only in non-frozen CPython environments with
  modules other than __main__.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in django.forms.renderers by
  removing the undocumented, module-level constant ROOT, which had been
  used in only one cached property.

* Prevented a crash during Django pre-alpha development if __file__ is
  missing by teaching django.utils.version.get_git_changeset to return
  None instead of raising NameError.

  django.__version__ is computed when django is first imported. If
  django.VERSION is pre-alpha, django.utils.version.get_version
  calls django.utils.version.get_git_changeset.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in django.views.debug by
  by removing the the undocumented, module-level constant CURRENT_DIR,
  which had been used only in the module itself. Replaced it with a
  module-level  private function `builtin_template_path` that refactors
  and centralizes finding built-in templates for the entire module.

  Converted the html_template_path and text_template_path class attributes of
  django.views.debug.ExceptionReporter (added in #32105, GH-13531) to be
  classproperty to maintain backward compatibility, and added tests for that.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in
  django.contrib.auth.password_validation by converting
  CommonPasswordValidator's class constant DEFAULT_PASSWORD_LIST_PATH
  into a cached property. It is used only in one place, the class's
  instance constructor. While the nature of DEFAULT_PASSWORD_LIST_PATH
  is not documented, its existence can be inferred from the docs for the
  [constructor's signature].

  [constructor's signature]: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/3.1/topics/auth/passwords/#django.contrib.auth.password_validation.CommonPasswordValidator

  During review there was some [back]-[and]-[forth] about whether to use Python
  3.8's functools.cached_property (GH-13915 raised the minimum supported
  version to 3.8) or django.utils.functional.cached_property, but settled on
  the latter.

  [back]: https://github.com/django/django/pull/13841#discussion_r551560566
  [and]: https://github.com/django/django/pull/13841#discussion_r570091753
  [forth]: https://github.com/django/django/pull/13841#discussion_r601156906

Thanks to @carltongibson, @orf, @shreyasravi, and @felixxm for review and
feedback.

Simplified and optimized test_match_tags().

This simplifies and optimizes runner.py's test_match_tags() because it
(1) uses isdisjoint() instead of intersection(), which involves
constructing a new set, (2) eliminates a set operation when tags is
falsey, (3) eliminates the need for a matched_tags variable, and (4)
uses fewer not's, which should make it easier to parse and understand.

Add file access modes to file upload example

The example for how to write a test that involves submitting a file involves uploading a binary file, but doesn't have a file access mode set. Since Python defaults to reading the file as text, this can result in UnicodeDecodeErrors.

This change adds an access_mode of 'rb' to the example thus causing Python to interpret it as a binary file.

Fixed #32316 -- Deferred accessing __file__.

Deferred accessing the module-global variable __file__ because the
Python import API does not guarantee it always exists—in particular, it
does not exist in certain "frozen" environments. The following changes
advanced this goal.

* Corrected or removed misleading code comments.

  The comment in questioner.py about needing getattr() for __file__ only
  in PY36 and older is true only in non-frozen CPython environments with
  modules other than __main__.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in django.forms.renderers by
  removing the undocumented, module-level constant ROOT, which had been
  used in only one cached property.

* Prevented a crash during Django pre-alpha development if __file__ is
  missing by teaching django.utils.version.get_git_changeset to return
  None instead of raising NameError.

  django.__version__ is computed when django is first imported. If
  django.VERSION is pre-alpha, django.utils.version.get_version
  calls django.utils.version.get_git_changeset.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in django.views.debug by
  by removing the the undocumented, module-level constant CURRENT_DIR,
  which had been used only in the module itself. Replaced it with a
  module-level  private function `builtin_template_path` that refactors
  and centralizes finding built-in templates for the entire module.

  Converted the html_template_path and text_template_path class attributes of
  django.views.debug.ExceptionReporter (added in #32105, GH-13531) to be
  classproperty to maintain backward compatibility, and added tests for that.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in
  django.contrib.auth.password_validation by converting
  CommonPasswordValidator's class constant DEFAULT_PASSWORD_LIST_PATH
  into a cached property. It is used only in one place, the class's
  instance constructor. While the nature of DEFAULT_PASSWORD_LIST_PATH
  is not documented, its existence can be inferred from the docs for the
  [constructor's signature].

  [constructor's signature]: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/3.1/topics/auth/passwords/#django.contrib.auth.password_validation.CommonPasswordValidator

  During review there was some [back]-[and]-[forth] about whether to use Python
  3.8's functools.cached_property (GH-13915 raised the minimum supported
  version to 3.8) or django.utils.functional.cached_property, but settled on
  the latter.

  [back]: https://github.com/django/django/pull/13841#discussion_r551560566
  [and]: https://github.com/django/django/pull/13841#discussion_r570091753
  [forth]: https://github.com/django/django/pull/13841#discussion_r601156906

Thanks to @carltongibson, @orf, @shreyasravi, and @felixxm for review and
feedback.

  django.VERSION is pre-alpha, django.utils.version.get_version
  calls django.utils.version.get_git_changeset.

  which had been used only in the module itself. Replaced it with a
  module-level  private function `builtin_template_path` that refactors

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in

  3.8's functools.cached_property (GH-13915 raised the minimum supported
  version to 3.8) or django.utils.functional.cached_property, but settled on

Fixed #32316 -- Deferred accessing __file__.

Deferred accessing the module-global variable __file__ because the
Python import API does not guarantee it always exists—in particular, it
does not exist in certain "frozen" environments. The following changes
advanced this goal.

* Corrected or removed misleading code comments.

  The comment in questioner.py about needing getattr() for __file__ only
  in PY36 and older is true only in non-frozen CPython environments with
  modules other than __main__.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in django.forms.renderers by
  removing the undocumented, module-level constant ROOT, which had been
  used in only one cached property.

* Prevented a crash during Django pre-alpha development if __file__ is
  missing by teaching django.utils.version.get_git_changeset to return
  None instead of raising NameError.

  django.__version__ is computed when django is first imported. If
  django.VERSION is pre-alpha, django.utils.version.get_version
  calls django.utils.version.get_git_changeset.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in django.views.debug by
  by removing the the undocumented, module-level constant CURRENT_DIR,
  which had been used only in the module itself. Replaced it with a
  module-level  private function `_builtin_template_path` that refactors
  and centralizes finding built-in templates for the entire module.

  The one tricky part was that #32105 (GH-13531) added the
  html_template_path and text_template_path attributes
  django.views.debug.ExceptionReporter. Avoided disturbing #32105's goal
  of making the template paths easily override-able by not calling
  _builtin_template_path in the class definition. Instead, detected the
  presence of the attributes in __init__ and set defaults there.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in
  django.contrib.auth.password_validation by converting
  CommonPasswordValidator's class constant DEFAULT_PASSWORD_LIST_PATH
  into a cached property. It is used only in one place, the class's
  instance constructor. While the nature of DEFAULT_PASSWORD_LIST_PATH
  is not documented, its existence can be inferred from the docs for the
  [constructor's signature].

  [constructor's signature]: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/3.1/topics/auth/passwords/#django.contrib.auth.password_validation.CommonPasswordValidator

  Used Python 3.8's functools.cached_property rather than the one from
  django.utils.functional as requested in [review] (#13915 will raise
  the minimum supported version to 3.8).

  [review]: https://github.com/django/django/pull/13841#discussion_r570091753

Fixed #32572 -- Unwrapped functools.partial objects in ResolverMatch.__init__().

When a partial function was passed as the view, the ``__repr__`` would
show the ``func`` argument as ``functools.partial`` which isn't very
helpful, especially as it doesn't reveal the underlying function or
arguments provided.

Because a partial function also has arguments provided up front, we need
to handle those specially so that they are accessible in ``__repr__``.
But it doesn't make sense storing extra attributes to pass through to
``__repr__`` when we already have all the deconstructed parts.

tries to access a URL with a colon (:) or pipe (|) in it. It fails
on Windows, but not on Linux.

This is likely related to the way Windows handles some characters
in file / directory names.

Fully automate dev setup with Gitpod

This commit implements a fully-automated development setup using Gitpod.io, an
online IDE for GitLab, GitHub, and Bitbucket that enables Dev-Environments-As-Code.
This makes it easy for anyone to get a ready-to-code workspace for any branch,
issue or pull request almost instantly with a single click.

Fully automate dev setup with Gitpod

This commit implements a fully-automated development setup using Gitpod.io, an
online IDE for GitLab, GitHub, and Bitbucket that enables Dev-Environments-As-Code.
This makes it easy for anyone to get a ready-to-code workspace for any branch,
issue or pull request almost instantly with a single click.

Django intro tutorial captured in Windows DOS batch file

- Intended for beginners, development and/or learning purposes only.
- Since this showcases the final product of the tutorial then it is highly recommended to complete the tutorial prior to using this batch file.
- Tested as working in Windows 10 with: python 3.6.8 and django 3.1.7.
- Running the file for the first time will attempt to create django project, directory and file structure, setup database, create admin account and run the server.
- Subsequent attempts to run this file will only initiate an attempt to run the server (for as long as the "mysite" folder is detected).

Fixed #32316 -- Deferred accessing __file__.

Deferred accessing the module-global variable __file__ because the
Python import API does not guarantee it always exists—in particular, it
does not exist in certain "frozen" environments. The following changes
advanced this goal.

* Corrected or removed misleading code comments.

  The comment in questioner.py about needing getattr() for __file__ only
  in PY36 and older is true only in non-frozen CPython environments with
  modules other than __main__.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in django.forms.renderers by
  removing the undocumented, module-level constant ROOT, which had been
  used in only one cached property.

* Prevented a crash during Django pre-alpha development if __file__ is
  missing by teaching django.utils.version.get_git_changeset to return
  None instead of raising NameError.

  django.__version__ is computed when django is first imported. If
  django.VERSION is pre-alpha, django.utils.version.get_version
  calls django.utils.version.get_git_changeset.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in django.views.debug by
  by removing the the undocumented, module-level constant CURRENT_DIR,
  which had been used only in the module itself. Replaced it with a
  module-level  private function `_builtin_template_path` that refactors
  and centralizes finding built-in templates for the entire module.

  The one tricky part was that #32105 (GH-13531) added the
  html_template_path and text_template_path attributes
  django.views.debug.ExceptionReporter. Avoided disturbing #32105's goal
  of making the template paths easily override-able by not calling
  _builtin_template_path in the class definition. Instead, detected the
  presence of the attributes in __init__ and set defaults there.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in
  django.contrib.auth.password_validation by converting
  CommonPasswordValidator's class constant DEFAULT_PASSWORD_LIST_PATH
  into a cached property. It is used only in one place, the class's
  instance constructor. While the nature of DEFAULT_PASSWORD_LIST_PATH
  is not documented, its existence can be inferred from the docs for the
  [constructor's signature].

  [constructor's signature]: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/3.1/topics/auth/passwords/#django.contrib.auth.password_validation.CommonPasswordValidator

Fixed #32316 -- Deferred accessing __file__.

Deferred accessing the module-global variable __file__ because the
Python import API does not guarantee it always exists—in particular, it
does not exist in certain "frozen" environments. The following changes
advanced this goal.

* Corrected or removed misleading code comments.

  The comment in questioner.py about needing getattr() for __file__ only
  in PY36 and older is true only in non-frozen CPython environments with
  modules other than __main__.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in django.forms.renderers by
  removing the undocumented, module-level constant ROOT, which had been
  used in only one cached property.

* Prevented a crash during Django pre-alpha development if __file__ is
  missing by teaching django.utils.version.get_git_changeset to return
  None instead of raising NameError.

  django.__version__ is computed when django is first imported. If
  django.VERSION is pre-alpha, django.utils.version.get_version
  calls django.utils.version.get_git_changeset.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in django.views.debug by
  by removing the the undocumented, module-level constant CURRENT_DIR,
  which had been used only in the module itself. Replaced it with a
  module-level  private function `_builtin_template_path` that refactors
  and centralizes finding built-in templates for the entire module.

  The one tricky part was that #32105 (GH-13531) added the
  html_template_path and text_template_path attributes
  django.views.debug.ExceptionReporter. Avoided disturbing #32105's goal
  of making the template paths easily override-able by not calling
  _builtin_template_path in the class definition. Instead, detected the
  presence of the attributes in __init__ and set defaults there.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in
  django.contrib.auth.password_validation by converting
  CommonPasswordValidator's class constant DEFAULT_PASSWORD_LIST_PATH
  into a cached property. It is used only in one place, the class's
  instance constructor. While the nature of DEFAULT_PASSWORD_LIST_PATH
  is not documented, its existence can be inferred from the docs for the
  [constructor's signature].

  [constructor's signature]: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/3.1/topics/auth/passwords/#django.contrib.auth.password_validation.CommonPasswordValidator

  Used Python 3.8's functools.cached_property rather than the one from
  django.utils.functional as requested in [review] (#13915 will raise
  the minimum supported version to 3.8).

  [review]: https://github.com/django/django/pull/13841#discussion_r570091753

Thanks to @carltongibson, @orf, and @shreyasravi for review and
feedback.

docs/ref/databases: rephrase persistent connections section

At first glance, I thought this section (and the whole page)
referred to requests to the database, hinting that Django would have
recreated connections to the database after each query.

In reality, Django manages that only in the context of `HttpRequest`
calls. Hence, this commit clarifies this behavior in the documentation.

Fixed #32446 -- Deprecated SERIALIZE test database setting.

Whether or not the state of a test database should be serialized can be
inferred from the set of databases allowed to be access from discovered
TestCase/TransactionTestCase enabling the serialized_rollback feature
which makes this setting unnecessary.

This should make a significant test suite bootstraping time difference
on large projects that didn't explicitly disable test database
serialization.

Copy: object._state.adding=True 

When creating a new object from an existing object, the description currently overlooks that the `object._state.adding` should be set to `True`. This may not matter in many cases, which can explain why this is left out here, but it does matter when using models with natural keys combined with third party packages as `object.pk` will not be a faly value in these cases.

It is currently an issue in https://github.com/django-treebeard/django-treebeard/issues/210 . I have contacted the original author of this section and his response can be found here: https://github.com/django/django/commit/a97ecfdea80080da7e522d8dd8a4792a777694f9#commitcomment-47314995

Fixed #32446 -- Deprecated the SERIALIZE test database setting.

Whether or not the state of a test database should be serialized can be
inferred from the set of databases allowed to be access from discovered
`TransactionTestCase` enabling the `serialized_rollback` feature which makes
this setting unnecessary.

This should make a significant test suite bootstraping time difference on large
projects that didn't explicitly disable test database serialization.

Fixed #29052 -- Made test database creation preserve alias order and prefer the "default" database.

This fixes flushing test databases when two aliases point to the same
database.

Use a list() to store the test database aliases so the order remains
stable by following the order of the connections. Also, always use the
"default" database alias as the first alias to accommodate `migrate`.

Previously `migrate` could be executed on a secondary alias which
caused truncating the "default" database.

Fixed #32316 -- Deferred accessing __file__.

Deferred accessing the module-global variable __file__ because the
Python import API does not guarantee it always exists—in particular, it
does not exist in certain "frozen" environments. The following changes
advanced this goal.

* Corrected or removed misleading code comments.

  The comment in questioner.py about needing getattr() for __file__ only
  in PY36 and older is true only in non-frozen CPython environments with
  modules other than __main__.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in django.forms.renderers by
  removing the undocumented, module-level constant ROOT, which had been
  used in only one cached property.

* Prevented a crash during Django pre-alpha development if __file__ is
  missing by teaching django.utils.version.get_git_changeset to return
  None instead of raising NameError.

  django.__version__ is computed when django is first imported. If
  django.VERSION is pre-alpha, django.utils.version.get_version
  calls django.utils.version.get_git_changeset.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in django.views.debug by
  by removing the the undocumented, module-level constant CURRENT_DIR,
  which had been used only in the module itself. Replaced it with a
  module-level  private function `_builtin_template_path` that refactors
  and centralizes finding built-in templates for the entire module.

  The one tricky part was that #32105 (GH-13531) added the
  html_template_path and text_template_path attributes
  django.views.debug.ExceptionReporter. Avoided disturbing #32105's goal
  of making the template paths easily override-able by not calling
  _builtin_template_path in the class definition. Instead, detected the
  presence of the attributes in __init__ and set defaults there.

* Avoided using __file__ at module level in
  django.contrib.auth.password_validation by converting
  CommonPasswordValidator's class constant DEFAULT_PASSWORD_LIST_PATH
  into a cached property. It is used only in one place, the class's
  instance constructor. While the nature of DEFAULT_PASSWORD_LIST_PATH
  is not documented, its existence can be inferred from the docs for the
  [constructor's signature].

  [constructor's signature]: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/3.1/topics/auth/passwords/#django.contrib.auth.password_validation.CommonPasswordValidator

  Used Python 3.8's functools.cached_property rather than the one from
  django.utils.functional as requested in [review] (#13915 will raise
  the minimum supported version to 3.8).

  [review]: https://github.com/django/django/pull/13841#discussion_r570091753

Thanks to @carltongibson, @orf, and @shreyasravi for review and
feedback.

Optimized _destruct_iterable_mapping_values.

Elements yielded by _destruct_iterable_mapping_values are always unpacked. Since unpacking can be done with any iterable, there is no need to convert elements to tuples if they are iterables.

Also, such elements can be used directly in for loops, creating a dictionary of them is excessive.

Modernized custom manager example

Since this example was added 15 years ago in a8ccdd0fcd631e8e928ef20547e1fe3e313dc607, the ORM has gained the ability to do the `COUNT(*)` related query, so do it with the ORM to avoid misleading users that raw SQL is only supported from manager methods.
